        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Most of the molecular lines have half widths of ~2.5-3 km/s. We will thus require the finest spectral resolution provided by the selected correlators. Some lines, such as CH3OH, SiO, and SO lines, are much broader, &gt;5 km/s. Although we would rather keep the nominal spectral resolution of the correlator in order to study the kinematics, we will consider spectral averaging for these lines when/if they are weak.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We require a full spectral scan at the finest spectral resolution of the correlators (0.8 km/s) in order to resolve the line profiles (typically ~2.5 - 3 km/s). For some broader lines (e.g. CH3OH, SiO, SO), spectral averaging can be applied in order to reduce the data rate.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_HIGH_DATA_RATE</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>OMC-2 FIR 4 occupies an area of around 20arcsec in diameter, but it is fragmented into multiple small cores of a few arcsec each or smaller. The interferometric images that have been obtained so far have resolutions of 3 arcsec or coarser, and they are not able to appropriately resolve each core within the region. The requested angular resolution of 0.5 arcsec (200 AU) is necessary to fulfill our goal of characterising each of the individual cores at the scales typical of disks and hot corinos (i.e. 100 to several AU).</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our requested line sensitivity of 6 mJy/beam should largely suffice to detect the strongest lines observed in this region with the IRAM 30-m telescope (i.e. dense gas tracers such as HCO+, HCN, as well as cold/pre-stellar gas traces such as carbon-chains), since we expect flux densities around 50 mJy/beam based on our single-dish data. On the other hand, shock tracers such as SiO, and hot corino tracers such as complex organic molecules are weaker in our single-dish dataset (&lt;~0.1K), but expected to be compact (~1arcsec) and thus considerably beam-diluted, in which case the requested sensitivity should be enough for ~5sigma detections or higher.

We will derive the 3-mm continuum flux associated with each molecular core in OMC-2 FIR 4 protocluster by averaging the line-free channels in our spectrum. A continuum sensitivity of 31.5 microJy will allow us to detect cold (T &lt; 10 K) compact cores down to masses of 0.1 Msun, and even smaller for warmer cores. Such small masses are an order of magnitude lower than what has been achieved so far for this region.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
