    <prp:abstract>The majority of stars in our Galaxy form in clusters. In particular, our Solar System was likely born in a large cluster containing massive stars. Understanding the formation of most of the stars, including our own, should therefore involve studying cluster formation. Despite this, a detailed characterisation of the individual cores within protoclusters is still lacking. Systematic spectral surveys are a powerful tool for this purpose, as they unbiasedly provide information on (1) chemical composition, (2) physical conditions through detection of multiple transitions of a given species, and (3) kinematics. We propose to conduct a spectral scan, between 85 and 93.8 GHz, of OMC-2 FIR4, i.e. the most similar environment to that of the proto-solar nebula identified so far. In this region, many elements of cluster formation can be characterised simultaneously (multiple cores, molecular outflow interaction, ionising radiation fields), as demonstrated by our single-dish spectral surveys of this source. The selected frequency window is optimised to cover multiple key lines based on our experience. High angular resolution (0.5") is mandatory to resolve the different components.</prp:abstract>
